<TITLE> Notice on govt asks to save Dhaka rivers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 19 (bdnews24.com)A human-rights organisation served a legal notice asking the government to take steps to protect rivers Buriganga, Sitalakhya and Turag and demanding demolition of illegal installations on the river embankments. President of Human Rights and Peace for Bangladesh advocate Manjil Morshed served notices on Tuesday on the planning secretary, environment secretary, land secretary, finance secretary, shipping secretary, Bangladesh Inland Water Transport Authority chairman, director general of the environment directorate, deputy commissioner of Dhaka and Dhaka Metropolitan Police commissioner. "The legal notices were served on them to take steps within four days. If the government fails to take action by that time, a writ petition will be filed in the High Court next week," Morshed told bdnews24.com. The notice said: "According to the law of the land, it is illegal to divert natural condition of a river. But illegal occupants fill the place with earth and are obstructing the normal flow of the river by setting up temporary and permanent establishments thereon, threatening the environment." b
